"{\"uid\": \"straitstimes.com-sport-under-a-soft-rain-at-the-paris-olympics-hardy-rowers-use-the-power-of-words\", \"text\": \"Choose edition  Search  singapore  asia  world  opinion  life  business  sport  Visual  Podcasts  SPH Rewards  STClassifieds  Paid press releases  Advertise with us  FAQs  Contact us  Sporting Life  Sign up now:Get the biggest sports news in your inbox  Singapore rower Saiyidah Aisyah scribbles words in her journal, a sort of raw accounting of her days.  ST PHOTO: MARK CHEONG  Rohit Brijnath  Published\\u00c2Jul 27, 2024, 11:04 PM  Updated\\u00c2Jul 28, 2024, 01:21 AM  PARIS\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0093The name of a stranger from a foreign land is written on a sticker in Jacob Plihal\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s boat.  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cKim,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d it says.  She isn\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t Plihal\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s friend, she isn\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t family. This polite, 2.08m American hasn\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t even ever met the Australian. But under a gently pecking rain at the Vaires-sur-Marne Nautical Stadium in Paris, as we discuss motivation, this 28-year-old with an architectural degree mentions her name.  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cI\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099ll put little stickers in my boat sometimes,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d explains Plihal. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cLike a little mantra that\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s been impactful lately. So one that comes to mind is just a name, Kim Brennan.  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cShe was an Australian rower, single sculler, very successful, won (gold at) the 2016 Olympics. And I think she\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s a very good influence on technique. So just writing \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cKim\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d in my boat, I see that and I visualise how she rows and that\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s someone I try to model (myself on).\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  These Games are fiercer than we can imagine and races unfold like hasty, unforgiving interrogations. Just to make it clear, the Italian fencer Luigi Samele put it bluntly: \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cThe goal of the Olympics, of course, is not to have a nice walk around the Olympic Village, but to go home with medals\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d.  But in this festival committed to the athletic deeds, don\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t underestimate the power of words. Coaches in Paris shout them. Psychologists use them as balm. Athletes mutter them in call rooms. And sometimes, as with former medal-winning gymnast Louis Smith, they even tattoo reminders onto their arms: \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cWhat I Deserve I Earn\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d.  Singapore rower Saiyidah Aisyah scribbles words in her journal, a sort of raw accounting of her days. Words to rise to and go to sleep with. Words to wear like armour. Words that before Rio 2016 \\u00e2\\u0080\\u0093 the first Olympics she qualified for \\u00e2\\u0080\\u0093 she pasted to her wall almost in the thousands. Some were truths, some a plea, some an athletic prayer.  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cTrain to be bulletproof\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d.  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cIt is meant to be hard\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d.  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cI am *&^%^& amazing.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  This year, making a comeback after stepping away from the sport, Aisyah turned to words again. Filled her journal with scribbles as if writing them down was reassurance. Just before the Games she shared two pages of them with The Straits Times.  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cI am strong, lifting heavy at the gym, 11 on the chin ups. Powerful.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cI have done this before. Trust. Let go.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cI know what pain feels like. I feel it every day out there on water. This is nothing different.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  Incredibly after barely a year back, Aisyah qualified for Paris but on July 27, under a sulky grey sky, she couldn\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t find her best self. In Rio, in her quarter-finals, she timed 7min 56sec across 2,000m; in Paris,in the heats where she came fifth out of five competitors, she stopped the clock at 8:17.04.  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cI know what I can do,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d she said later, being unsparing with her words \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cand I did not do it today. The power was just not there. The speed was not there. Rowing is simple. It\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s just put the blades in and take the blades out. And sometimes you may make it more complicated.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  Rowers embody strength, as if they\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099re massive human engines fitted neatly into slim boats. But these gleaming bodies, these flat, competitive faces, are partly lies. In sport, toughness always resides beside insecurity. Behind everyone\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s fibre, doubt rustles.  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009c(I\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099m) definitely trying to keep strong, positive thoughts,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d says Olympic first-timer Paige Badenhorst of South Africa. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cAcknowledging the demons that, yes, I\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099m nervous, everyone else is nervous. But also reminding myself of my strengths, what you do have that will help you fight those demons.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  To ward off these demons is to reach for words. To remind themselves of who they are. What they\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099ve done. How they\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099ve earned their way here. And so Badenhorst, part of the 2022 Cambridge crew who won the annual Boat Race on the River Thames, has words echoing in her head.  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cCalm. Cool. Collected.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cFierce. Ruthless.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cJust repeat those words to myself.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  During a race?  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cBefore, during, after,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d she says with laugh.  And it\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s not just her, it\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s champions who reach for words to achieve that perfect state they\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099re searching for. Emma Twigg, 37, is the defending Olympic champion in the women\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s single sculls, has a licence to skipper boats, can repair cycles and has an academic degree in sports. Still for all this, for all her four Games before Paris, she needs to talk to herself at the start.  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cYou\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099ve done this a million times.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  Twigg is surging forward, Aisyah has one more chance on July 28 in the repechage. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cIt\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s me just against myself and whatever is in my head,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d she said a little mournfully. There\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s no guarantee in sport, but there is one thing you can be sure she did after her race.  She went back to the Village. Pulled out her journal. And found some refuge in words.  Sporting Life  Olympics 2024  Singapore athletes  Rowing  Team Singapore  E-paper  Newsletters  Podcasts  RSS Feed  About Us  Terms & Conditions  Personal Data Protection Notice  Need help? Reach us here.  Advertise with us    \"}"